solution:
```json
PUT /pilots
{
  "mappings": {
    "properties": {
      "personal_id":        { "type": "keyword" },
      "name":               { "type": "keyword" },
      "surname":            { "type": "keyword" },
      "birth_date":         { "type": "date", "format": "yyyy-MM-dd" },
      "gender":             { "type": "keyword" },
      "championships_won":  { "type": "integer" },
      "career":             { "type": "text", "analyzer": "standard" }
    }
  }
}
```
`personal_id`, `name`, `surname`, and `gender` are `keyword` (exact-match/aggregatable, not analyzed), `birth_date` is a `date`, `championships_won` is numeric (`integer`), and `career` — the only free-text/textual attribute — is `text` so it is tokenized and searchable by the full-text queries required later in the exercise.

```json
GET /pilots/_search
{
  "query": {
    "bool": {
      "filter": [
        { "term":  { "gender": "M" } },
        { "range": { "championships_won": { "gte": 10 } } }
      ],
      "must": [
        { "match": { "career": { "query": "Champion Car", "operator": "and" } } }
      ],
      "should": [
        { "match": { "career": "Young" } }
      ]
    }
  }
}
```
`filter` enforces the hard, non-scoring constraints (male, ≥10 championships); `must` with `operator: and` requires both "Champion" and "Car" to appear in `career`; `should` adds "Young" as an optional clause that boosts the relevance score of documents that also contain it, without excluding those that don't.

**Number of collections: 3** — `teams` (embedding the 1:1 Team Owner, since a Team has exactly one Owner and vice versa, and a Team's roster of Pilots/Engineers/Mechanics is naturally embedded as it changes together with the team and is bounded in size), `races` (each Race records the Pilots who competed via a reference, since a Pilot competes in many Races and a Race has many Pilots — a many-to-many best modeled with references to avoid unbounded/duplicated arrays), and — because Team Member subtypes are queried individually — one could also keep pilots as embedded sub-documents inside `teams` while `races` references them by `personal_id`.

Example document:
```json
// teams collection
{
  "_id": "T1",
  "team_name": "Scuderia Rossa",
  "foundation_date": "1950-01-01",
  "owner": {
    "personal_id": "P100",
    "name": "Mario",
    "surname": "Trenti",
    "birth_date": "1970-05-03",
    "gender": "M",
    "total_assets": 500000000,
    "biography": "..."
  },
  "members": [
    { "personal_id": "P200", "name": "Luca", "surname": "Bianchi", "birth_date": "1995-01-01",
      "gender": "M", "role": "Pilot", "championships_won": 2, "career": "..." },
    { "personal_id": "P201", "name": "Anna", "surname": "Verdi", "birth_date": "1988-01-01",
      "gender": "F", "role": "Engineer", "role_description": "..." },
    { "personal_id": "P202", "name": "Gino", "surname": "Neri", "birth_date": "1980-01-01",
      "gender": "M", "role": "Mechanic", "role_description": "..." }
  ]
}

// races collection
{
  "_id": "R1",
  "laps_number": 58,
  "max_tickets": 50000,
  "date": "2020-09-06",
  "pilots": [
    { "pilot_id": "P200", "winner": true, "fastest_lap": "1:21.046" }
  ]
}
```
Owner and current team members are embedded (1:1 and bounded 1:N, updated together with the team), while the many-to-many Pilot–Race relationship (`Compete`) is implemented by referencing pilot ids inside each race document, avoiding unbounded growth of either side.

```javascript
db.teams.aggregate([
  { $match: { "owner.surname": "Trenti" } },
  { $project: {
      numPilots: {
        $size: {
          $filter: {
            input: "$members",
            as: "m",
            cond: { $eq: ["$$m.role", "Pilot"] }
          }
        }
      }
  }},
  { $match: { numPilots: { $gt: 5 } } },
  { $count: "totalTeams" }
])
```
The pipeline first keeps teams owned by a "Trenti", counts each team's embedded members with `role: "Pilot"`, filters to teams with more than 5 such pilots, and finally counts the resulting teams.

```javascript
db.races.aggregate([
  { $unwind: "$pilots" },
  { $group: {
      _id: "$pilots.pilot_id",
      totalRaces: { $sum: 1 },
      teams: { $addToSet: "$pilots.team_id" }
  }},
  { $match: { totalRaces: { $gte: 100 } } },
  { $project: {
      _id: 0,
      pilot_id: "$_id",
      numTeams: { $size: "$teams" }
  }}
])
```
This assumes each entry in a race's `pilots` array also records the `team_id` the pilot raced for in that race (needed to distinguish teams, since a pilot may have changed teams across their career). The pipeline unwinds races per pilot appearance, counts each pilot's total career races and collects the distinct teams they raced for, keeps only pilots with ≥100 races, and reports the number of distinct teams for each.
